---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import ChainOfTrust from '@/components/react/ChainOfTrust.tsx';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="The chain of trust"
  description="How OSNMA links a single out-of-band anchor all the way down to authenticated navigation data."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="4 · Cryptographic machinery"
    title="The chain of trust, end to end"
    lead="Every OSNMA mechanism on this site is one link in a single chain. Each link is authenticated by the one above it — from a value you trust out-of-band down to the data in your position fix."
  />

  <p>
    Pull the pieces together. The Merkle tree, the ECDSA signature, the TESLA chain
    and the tags each solve one hand-off of trust. Stacked, they let a receiver
    that trusts only one downloaded value end up trusting live navigation data from
    every satellite in view.
  </p>

  <ChainOfTrust client:visible />

  <h2>The single rule</h2>
  <p>
    Read top to bottom, the pattern never changes: <strong>nothing is trusted until
    something already trusted vouches for it.</strong> The Merkle root vouches for
    the public key; the public key's signature vouches for KROOT; KROOT vouches for
    every TESLA key; each key vouches for its tags; and a matching tag vouches for
    the navigation data.
  </p>

  <Callout type="security">
    <p>
      Break any link and the chain stops: an unverified public key cannot validate
      a KROOT signature, and an unanchored key cannot validate a tag. That is why a
      receiver rebuilds exactly the missing links at start-up — and no more. See
      <a href="/receiver/startup">cold / warm / hot start</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      The two ends differ in trust model on purpose: the top uses
      <strong>asymmetric</strong> cryptography (Merkle hashing and ECDSA signatures),
      which is robust but heavy, just rarely; the bottom uses cheap
      <strong>symmetric</strong> MACs every second, made trustworthy by TESLA's
      delayed disclosure.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
